# NixOS Podman Rootless Setup Guide

> Generated by qsdev. This document provides NixOS-specific configuration
> for running Podman in rootless mode as a development container runtime.

## 1. System-Level Podman Configuration

Enable Podman at the system level in your NixOS configuration
(`/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` or equivalent):

```nix
virtualisation = {
  containers.enable = true;
  podman = {
    enable = true;
    dockerCompat = true;
    defaultNetwork.settings.dns_enabled = true;
  };
};
```

- `virtualisation.podman.enable` installs Podman and its dependencies.
- `dockerCompat = true` creates a `docker` symlink pointing to `podman`,
  enabling drop-in replacement for scripts and tools that expect `docker`.
- `dns_enabled = true` enables inter-container DNS on the default network,
  required for service discovery (e.g., `http://db:5432`) in multi-container
  setups.

## 2. Subordinate UID/GID Ranges (subUidRanges / subGidRanges)

Rootless Podman requires subordinate UID and GID ranges for user namespace
mapping. Without these, container creation fails with "user namespaces not
mapped."

Add the ranges to your user declaration:

```nix
users.users.{{ .Username }} = {
  isNormalUser = true;
  subUidRanges = [{ startUid = 100000; count = 65536; }];
  subGidRanges = [{ startGid = 100000; count = 65536; }];
};
```

NixOS writes these to `/etc/subuid` and `/etc/subgid` during system
activation. A re-login or reboot is required after adding these ranges
for the first time.

## 3. Systemd User PATH (/run/wrappers/bin)

NixOS places setuid helper binaries (`newuidmap`, `newgidmap`) in
`/run/wrappers/bin`. User systemd services do not include this path by
default, causing rootless container creation to fail because the
namespace-mapping helpers cannot be found.

Add the wrapper path to the default user systemd environment:

```nix
systemd.user.extraConfig = ''
  DefaultEnvironment="PATH=/run/current-system/sw/bin:/run/wrappers/bin"
'';
```

Without this, any rootless Podman operation launched from a user systemd
service (including socket-activated containers and quadlet units) will
fail with a `newuidmap: not found` error.

## 4. Linger (Background Services Without Login)

By default, user systemd services stop when the user logs out. For
containers that must run as persistent background services, enable
linger:

```nix
users.users.{{ .Username }} = {
  # ... other settings ...
  linger = true;
};
```

This is equivalent to `loginctl enable-linger {{ .Username }}` but
declaratively managed by NixOS. Without linger, all rootless containers
stop when you close your terminal session or SSH connection.

## 5. Declarative Rootless Containers with quadlet-nix

For declarative, NixOS-style management of rootless containers, use
`quadlet-nix`. It wraps Podman's native Quadlet functionality (systemd
generator for `.container` / `.pod` / `.network` unit files) in a Home
Manager module.

Add the flake input:

```nix
# In flake.nix
inputs.quadlet-nix.url = "github:SEIAROTg/quadlet-nix";
```

Import the Home Manager module and declare containers:

```nix
# In Home Manager configuration (home.nix)
imports = [ inputs.quadlet-nix.homeManagerModules.quadlet ];

services.quadlet.containers.myapp = {
  containerConfig = {
    image = "docker.io/nginx:latest";
    publishPort = [ "8080:80" ];
  };
  serviceConfig.Restart = "always";
  installConfig.wantedBy = [ "default.target" ];
};
```

This approach is cleaner than hand-rolling user systemd services and
maps directly to Podman's native Quadlet format.

Note: The system-level `virtualisation.oci-containers` module runs
containers as root, not as the invoking user. For rootless containers
managed declaratively, Home Manager with quadlet-nix is the correct
approach.

## 6. Storage Configuration (overlay)

Rootless Podman stores images and containers in
`~/.local/share/containers/`. The recommended storage driver is overlay.

Create `~/.config/containers/storage.conf`:

```ini
[storage]
driver = "overlay"
```

On Linux kernels 5.12 and later (all current NixOS kernels qualify),
native unprivileged overlayfs is used automatically. Older kernels fall
back to `fuse-overlayfs`.

If switching storage drivers, delete `~/.local/share/containers/storage`
first -- the database format is driver-specific and will fail if
mismatched.

**ZFS note:** If your home directory is on a ZFS dataset, ensure
`acltype=posixacl` is set on the dataset. Podman's storage layer
requires POSIX ACL support.

## 7. Docker Compose Integration (DOCKER_HOST)

To use `docker-compose` or `docker compose` with Podman's socket, set
the `DOCKER_HOST` environment variable to point at the Podman socket:

```bash
export DOCKER_HOST="unix://$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/podman/podman.sock"
```

In Home Manager, declare this persistently:

```nix
home.sessionVariables = {
  DOCKER_HOST = "unix:///run/user/1000/podman/podman.sock";
};
```

Enable the Podman socket so it is available for Compose:

```nix
# In Home Manager
systemd.user.sockets.podman = {
  Socket.ListenStream = "%t/podman/podman.sock";
  Install.WantedBy = [ "sockets.target" ];
};
```

Install `docker-compose` as a system package:

```nix
environment.systemPackages = with pkgs; [ docker-compose ];
```

## 8. Known NixOS-Specific Issues

### cgroups Delegation

NixOS enables cgroups v2 by default. If resource limits on rootless
containers are not working, verify that delegation is enabled for user
slices. NixOS should handle this when `virtualisation.podman.enable =
true`, but you can confirm by checking for a drop-in at
`/etc/systemd/system/user@.service.d/delegate.conf`:

```ini
[Service]
Delegate=yes
```

### Pasta vs slirp4netns Networking

Podman 5 defaults to Pasta for rootless networking. This may conflict
with NixOS firewall rules. If container networking fails, try
`--network=slirp4netns` as a fallback:

```bash
podman run --network=slirp4netns ...
```

### Reboot After subuid/subgid Changes

After adding `subUidRanges` / `subGidRanges` to your NixOS
configuration and rebuilding, a re-login (or reboot) is required for the
changes to take effect in the user's session.

## Complete Example

Combining all sections into a single NixOS configuration snippet:

```nix
{ config, pkgs, ... }:
{
  virtualisation = {
    containers.enable = true;
    podman = {
      enable = true;
      dockerCompat = true;
      defaultNetwork.settings.dns_enabled = true;
    };
  };

  users.users.{{ .Username }} = {
    isNormalUser = true;
    subUidRanges = [{ startUid = 100000; count = 65536; }];
    subGidRanges = [{ startGid = 100000; count = 65536; }];
    linger = true;
  };

  systemd.user.extraConfig = ''
    DefaultEnvironment="PATH=/run/current-system/sw/bin:/run/wrappers/bin"
  '';

  environment.systemPackages = with pkgs; [ docker-compose ];
}
```

After applying with `nixos-rebuild switch`, log out and back in (or
reboot) to activate the subordinate UID/GID ranges.
